,"East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1350–1372":"1350–1372","1350–1379":"1350–1379","1385–1469":"1385–1469","1346–1403":"1346–1403","1372–1416":"1372–1416","1373–1403":"1373–1403","1374–1420":"1374–1420","1375–Male":"1375–Deceased","1378–Male":"1378–Deceased","1320–1411":"1320–1411","1322–1390":"1322–1390","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1373":"1373","1350":"1350","1372":"1372","1371":"1371","Abt 1345":"about 1345","1390":"1390","1403":"1403","1469":"1469","1346":"1346","1379":"1379","1411":"1411","1378":"1378","1322":"1322","1420":"1420","1320":"1320","1375":"1375","1416":"1416","Knotishall,Suffolk,Eng":"Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","East Herling, Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","East Harling, Norfolk, England":"East Harling, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gyney","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Geigheannaigh</b> or <b>Mac Géibheannaigh</b>, see   Gainey  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain and Ireland."],"variants":[{"name":"Gainey","meanings":["Irish (Cork): shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Geigheannaigh</b> or <b>Mac Géibheannaigh</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Géibheannach</i>’, a byname meaning ‘fettered’."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Gyney was born in 1350, in East Harling, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, Sir Thomas de Gyney or Jenney, was 31 and her mother, Elizabeth Bourne, was 28. She married John de Herling in 1371, in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents o